      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me with this python function? its for my uni tech comp sci lab and the automated grader keeps failing me cuz it says \"time limit exceeded.\" i need to optimize the time complexity so it passes the big test cases (n > 10^7) or i'm gonna lose points. basically just make it fast enough to pass.\n\nhere is the code:\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        count = 0\n        for j in range(1, i + 1):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                count += 1\n        results.append(count)\n    return sum(results)\n\nhow do i make this run fast enough so the grader doesn't time out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue with your code is that it has a time complexity of O(n^2) due to the nested loops. We can optimize this by using the fact that the number of divisors of a number is equal to the product of the exponents of its prime factors plus one. Here's the optimized code:\n\n```python\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    def prime_factors(x):\n        factors = {}\n        i = 2\n        while i * i <= x:\n            if x % i:\n                i += 1\n            else:\n                x //= i\n                factors[i] = factors.get(i, 0) + 1\n        if x > 1:\n            factors[x] = factors.get(x, 0) + 1\n        return factors\n\n    def count_divisors(x):\n        factors = prime_factors(x)\n        count = 1\n        for factor in factors.values():\n            count *= (factor + 1)\n        return count\n\n    results = [count_divisors(i) for i in range(1, n + 1)]\n    return sum(results)\n```\n\nThis code first calculates the prime factors of each number, then uses these factors to calculate the number of divisors. This",
